'''Christine Mary Rutherford Fowler''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|sep=,|FRAS|FGS|FRCGS}} (born 1950), known as '''Mary Fowler''', is a British [[geologist]] and academic. Since 2012, she has served as the [[Master (college)|Master]] of [[Darwin College, Cambridge]]. She was previously a lecturer at [[Royal Holloway, University of London]], rising to become [[Dean (education)|Dean]] of its Faculty of Science.

==Early life and education==
Fowler was born in 1950 to Peter and Rosemary Fowler.<ref name="WW 2018">{{cite web|title=Fowler, Prof. (Christine) Mary Rutherford|website=[[Who's Who 2018]]|publisher=Oxford University Press|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.246624|date=1 December 2017}}</ref> She comes from a family of eminent scientists. A great-grandfather was [[Ernest Rutherford]], the 'father of nuclear physics', and her grandfather, Rutherford's son-in-law, was the mathematical physicist [[Ralph H. Fowler]].<ref name="Cambridge New Master">{{cite web|title=New Master for Darwin|url=http://www.cam.ac.uk/news/new-master-for-darwin|publisher=University of Cambridge|accessdate=3 May 2014|date=3 April 2012}}</ref>

She studied mathematics at [[Girton College, Cambridge]], graduating with a [[first class honours|first class]] [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) degree in 1972.<ref name="Cambridge New Master" /><ref name="WW 2018" /> In 1972 she joined [[Darwin College, Cambridge]] to undertake [[post-graduate studies]] in [[geophysics]] and completed her [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (PhD) degree in 1976.<ref name="Darwin New">{{cite web|title=New Master for Darwin College|url=https://www.darwin.cam.ac.uk/about/news/|website=News|publisher=Darwin College, Cambridge|accessdate=17 August 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819082651/http://www.darwin.cam.ac.uk/about/news/|archivedate=19 August 2014|df=}}</ref> Her [[doctoral thesis]] was titled "Seismic Studies of the Mid-Atlantic Ridge".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fowler|first1=C. M. R.|title=Seismic Studies of the Mid-Atlantic Ridge.|url=http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.455833|website=E-Thesis Online Service|publisher=The British Library Board|accessdate=21 January 2018|date=1976}}</ref>

==Academic career==
From 1977 to 1978, Fowler was a Royal Society European Fellow at [[ETH Zürich]] in Switzerland.<ref name="WW 2018" /> She joined the [[University of Saskatchewan]] in Canada as a [[research associate]] in 1981.<ref name="WW 2018" /><ref name="bio Darwin">{{cite web|title=Mary Fowler|url=http://www.darwin.cam.ac.uk/person/mary-fowler|website=Darwin College|publisher=University of Cambridge|accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref> She was an [[assistant professor]] from 1982 to 1983, before returning to her research associate position.<ref name="WW 2018" /> She remained associated with the university as an [[adjunct professor]] between 1991 and 2001.<ref name="WW 2018" />

In 1992, Fowler joined [[Royal Holloway, University of London]] as a [[lecturer]]; she was later promoted to [[senior lecturer]].<ref name="WW 2018" /><ref name="THE">{{cite news|title=Appointments|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/appointments/415870.article|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=Times Higher Education|date=21 April 2011}}</ref> Between 2002 and 2008, she was head of the Department of Earth Sciences.<ref name="THE" /> She was made [[Professor (highest academic rank)|Professor]] of Geophysics in 2003.<ref name="WW 2018" /> In 2011, she was appointed [[Dean (education)|Dean]] of the Faculty of Science.<ref name="WW 2018" /> 

In April 2012, it was announce that Fowler had been elected the sixth [[Master (college)|Master]] of [[Darwin College, Cambridge]].<ref name="Cambridge New Master" /> She took up the appointment in October 2012, succeeding [[William Brown (industrial relations expert)|William Brown]].<ref name="bio Darwin" />

==Personal life==
In 1975, Fowler married Euan Nisbet, now a Professor of Earth Sciences at Royal Holloway.<ref name="WW 2018" /><ref name="Four decades">{{cite news|last1=Baker|first1=Jennie|title=Four decades later, Mary returns|url=http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Education/Universities/Four-decades-later-Mary-returns-16102012.htm|accessdate=17 August 2014|work=Cambridge News|date=16 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Professor Euan Nisbet|url=http://pure.rhul.ac.uk/portal/en/persons/euan-nisbet_2ff4ba1e-64af-450c-b39d-eb64b7f809d1.html|website=Earth Sciences|publisher=Royal Holloway, University of London|accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref> They met at Darwin college, Cambridge while students.<ref name="Cambridge New Master" /><ref name="Four decades" /> Together, they have three children: two daughters and a son.<ref name="WW 2018" /> Their daughter (Ruth) Ellen Nisbet, who is a biochemist and academic, also studied at Darwin College, Cambridge.<ref name="Cambridge New Master" />

==Honours==
In 1996, Fowler was awarded the [[Prestwich Medal]] by the [[Geological Society of London]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Prestwich Medal|url=http://www.geolsoc.org.uk/About/History/Award-Winners-Since-1831/Prestwich-Medal|publisher=The Geological Society of London|accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref> She is a [[Fellow of the Royal Astronomical Society]] (FRAS), a [[Fellow of the Geological Society of London]] (FGS), and a [[Fellow of the Royal Canadian Geographical Society]] (FRCGS).<ref name="bio Darwin" /> In July 2018, Fowler was awarded an honorary [[Doctor of Science]] (DSc) by the [[University of Leeds]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leeds.ac.uk/info/130509/honorary_graduates/642/christine_mary_rutherford_fowler |title=Christine Mary Rutherford Fowler |publisher=University of Leeds |date=July 2018 |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> and by the [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ed.ac.uk/student-administration/graduations/honorary/future-honorary-grads|title=Honorary Graduates in 2018|work=The University of Edinburgh|access-date=2018-07-23|language=en}}</ref>

